          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px; 
              line-height: 1.2;  
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important; 
            ">US legacy in Vietnam</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/vietnam-parade-50th-anniversary-reunification-2025-china-laos-cambodia.png" alt="Vietnam held a parade with 13,000 participants to celebrate the 50th anniversary of national reunification, featuring troops from China, Laos, and Cambodia" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>
          Vietnam held a parade with 13,000 participants to celebrate the 50th anniversary of national reunification, featuring troops from China, Laos, and Cambodia. Credits: VN Express
            </i></p>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           The Vietnam War ended 50 years ago, and since then, the US-Vietnamese relations have improved. The Vietnamese government has welcomed guests from over 20 countries, including the US, to commemorate the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-30-04-2025-h1-1-reunification-day?source=website" target="_blank">Reunification Day</a>. However, the Trump administration has instructed US officials not to attend the military parade in Ho Chi Minh City. <p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
        Some Vietnamese view Trump’s move as a diplomatic snub. While US veterans and journalists will still visit Vietnam to honor the anniversary, the lack of official US participation shows that past wounds continue to affect US-Vietnamese relations. Event organizers said that more than 13,000 people, including the army, the police, and civilians, are taking part in the main parade. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          There are still visible effects of the war that remain, as many older Vietnamese people still experience post-traumatic stress. Another huge lingering issue is the widespread use of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #4D3060; color: black;" href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-30-04-2025-h1-2-agent-orange?source=website" target="_blank">Agent Orange</a> by the US. It is a toxic defoliant used during the war that caused lasting health issues for many. While the US has allocated over $155M for cleanup efforts, ongoing concerns persist about funding cuts and unfinished projects. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
